{
  "text": "CYCLONE is an orbit tracking code that can be used to study all regions of a cyclotron, but it is particularly suited for central region design work. Orbits are calculated using Runga-Kutta type integration in a variety of magnetic and electric field maps. The equations of motion used in CYCLONE are fully relativistic. The program is divided into three parts, each with a different integration approach. The first part integrates equations of motion in the given electric and magnetic field maps using time, as an independent variable. This is useful near the center of the cyclotron where orbits may deviate a lot from the circle. It is however slow because it needs to look up the magnetic field values at   FIG. 4 . Cell tune as a function of energy and peak current for 10 mm mrad beam [CITATION_1] . each step. The second part integrates equations of motion in electric and magnetic field maps but the azimuthal angle is taken as an independent variable. This is used for the first few turns in the cyclotron. The third part uses the angle as an independent variable, but the electric field is approximated by a delta function at the gaps. This is the fastest part and is used from the central region to the extraction system. Voltage variation as a function of the radius can be accommodated in part III. The program can step from one part to the next at the appropriate points. The program calculates both the median plane motion and vertical one. In part III the vertical motion is linear. In parts I and II the magnetic contribution is linear but the electric contribution can be either linear or nonlinear depending on the electric field mesh used.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "14047669"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "14047669": {
      "title": "Modeling space charge in an FFAG with ZGOUBI",
      "abstract": "The Zgoubi particle tracker uses a ray tracing algorithm that can accurately track particles with large offset from any reference momentum and trajectory, making it suitable for FFAGs. In high current FFAGs, for example an ADSR driver, space charge has a significant effect on the beam. A transverse space charge model was added to Zgoubi using the interface pyZgoubi. The magnets are sliced and a space charge kick is applied between each slice. Results are presented for an ADSR driver lattice."
    }
  }
}